<TITLE> NATO troops intervene as Kosovo border burns </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PRISTINA, Feb 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Troops of the NATO-led Kosovo peacekeeping force KFOR were being sent to the northern border of the newly independent republic on Tuesday to defend border posts under attack by Serbs who oppose its secession from Serbia. "KFOR is going to intervene now," spokesman Colonel Betrand Bonneau told Reuters. He declined to say which troops of the 35-nation force were being deployed. A second KFOR source said troops were already at one border post which had been burnt to the ground. Kosovo police called for help from NATO peacekeepers on Tuesday after Serbs opposed to Kosovo's newly declared independence burned down one border crossing and attacked another. Kosovo police took shelter in a tunnel at a border post near Zubin Potok in Kosovo's Serb-dominated north as more than 1,000 protesters tried to tear it down. "We asked NATO to send a helicopter to evacuate our officers," a police source told Reuters in Pristina. Troops of the NATO-led KFOR peacekeeping force in the district include French, Danish, Belgian and American uni
